entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 7 at 3:26PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
A storm force low in the western gulf will push a front towards the panhandle bringing gales to the outer coast and moderate precipitation to the panhandle late Friday morning through Saturday. With cold air in place, snow is expected at the onset of the event for the NE gulf coast and central and northern panhandle Friday before a transition to a mix and potentially rain for the Icy Strait corridor sometime Friday night or Saturday.
Forecasting snow totals for the inner channels for this event is highly dependent on the warm southerly push from the surface front making its way northward. While the pressure gradient ahead of the front does not support strong northerly outflow winds, the cold stable airmass in place over the panhandle will still be difficult to erode due to the front being so far displaced from the parent low in the western gulf.
With the surface front struggling to push inland and slowly dig away at the airmass over the panhandle, snow will become progressively wetter before transitioning to a mix or rain as late as Saturday early afternoon. A scenario of a later transition would lead to highest accumulations. Storm total accumulations of 10 to 15 inches possible (25% chance) for the Juneau area, with lesser totals closer to the outer coast. If the front is more progressive, the transition could occur as early as Friday night. This would significantly lower the overall snowfall totals for Icy Strait communities. Stay tuned for further updates as we head towards the weekend.
